  <discussion>Varieties 2 (2 in the flora):</discussion>
  <discussion>Trichodon cylindricus has a disjunct distribution in North America, where it is not uncommon in the northwestern part of the continent but is known from only a few scattered localities in the eastern part.  It has been collected from only a single locality each in Michigan (Keewenaw County), New Brunswick, and Ontario, and two localities each in Newfoundland and Quebec.  The distinctive gametophytes and sporophytes should aid collectors in finding additional eastern localities.  The distinctive characters of this species include the small plants, 2–4 mm high, with squarrose, subulate, acute leaves, and the slender, cylindric capsules.</discussion>
